THE QUEEN COMES HOME
A Chronicle of the Skyrim Wardens

PART I: THE SWORD ON THE FLOOR
The Stunned Moment
The cage sat a foot out of true on its wedge of unmeltable ice, and inside it the robes lay empty, and the corroded rapier lay among the robes, and the False Draugr crossed the laboratory floor in step with the patient inevitability of a tide.

Davinia did not move.

This was the part the others would remember, afterward, when they tried to reconstruct the order of things. Not the trap. Not the cage. Not even the empty coat settling into the breathing soil. What they remembered was Davinia standing at the edge of the displaced cage with her mace in the Wizard Hand and her stolen eyes fixed on the floor where Alfonso had been, and not moving, because some part of her — the part that was still a woman and not yet an architecture — had reached the precise threshold of horror where the body stops taking orders.

She had watched him die. She had watched the white pulse fill the cage and unmake the man cell by cell, and she had understood, in the way she understood everything now, exactly what she was looking at: an aura where an aura had been, and then no aura at all, and then a blade on the floor that blazed with the life the body used to hold. She had the whole truth before anyone else in the room had a single fact, and the truth had locked her in place.

The first False Draugr raised its weapon over her head.

And the Crown, which had been quiet company all day, stepped forward to cover her.

It did not ask. There was no time to ask, and asking was not what the moment required. Davinia felt herself slide sideways out of her own hands — a sensation she had no word for, like being moved gently to one side of a doorway by someone larger who needed through — and then she was watching from somewhere just behind her own eyes as her body did something she had not told it to do.

The Queen at the Wheel
The hand that was not quite Davinia's came up, palm open, fingers spread in a gesture that no College had ever taught, and the cold answered it the way a dog answers its own name.

It was not a spell. The party had seen Davinia cast a thousand times — the gathered Magicka, the somatic grammar, the effort of a mortal mind bending the world. This was none of that. This was a woman who had been cold for four thousand years simply deciding that the thing in front of her should stop, and the thing in front of her stopping. The False Draugr came apart in a single tonal shudder, frost blooming through its wet seams, and where it had been standing there was a statue, and then there was a scatter of frozen fragments, and then there was nothing worth naming at all.

The voice that came out of Davinia's mouth was Davinia's voice, but the cadence under it was older and entirely unhurried.

"There," it said. "That's the worst of them. You may have your hands back."

The Palace
And in the half-second of the handing-back — the moment between Ismara ceding the body and Davinia resuming it — Davinia saw where she had been living.

It was a palace.

She had perhaps half a heartbeat of it, the way you glimpse a lit room through a door swinging shut, and the glimpse was enough to keep her awake for nights afterward. A great hall of blue-white ice, vaulted and immense, every surface worked with the geometric precision of the writing she had read on the walls of the Midden. Galleries climbing into a ceiling she could not see. Corridors branching off corridors. And everywhere, in alcoves and on shelves and laid out on long tables of frozen crystal, things — catalogued, labelled, arranged with a researcher's loving exactitude. Her mother's lullaby, folded and stored. The warmth of a hand she could no longer place. The feeling of fire, which she had not been able to summon since Faralda's bridge, kept here behind glass like a specimen. The structure of a Void Atronach. A right hand of flesh. A breath that no longer came by itself.

Her life, taken apart and shelved. And the hall was not finished. There was scaffolding in the high galleries. There was a wing under construction. Ismara was building, room by patient room, a place to live that was made entirely of the things she had removed from Davinia, and she was not nearly done, and the palace was beautiful, and it was the most frightening thing Davinia had ever seen, because she understood at last that she was not its prisoner.

She was its foundation.

Then the door swung shut, and she was holding her own mace, and the laboratory was loud again, and there were three False Draugr left and a fight to finish.

She finished it. She was very good, and she had a great deal she needed not to think about, and the two things served each other. By the time the last construct fell she had stopped shaking, mostly, and she had decided — the way she decided most things, alone, in the place where Danica said she kept her control — that she would tell no one what she had seen.

The Bearer
The corroded rapier lay on the cage floor, under ice that would not melt, and it had not moved through any of it.

Saijah reached it first. She had to break the stabilized ice to do it — Davinia cracked the wedge with the Wizard Hand and the cage settled, freeing the blade — and Saijah crouched and picked the rapier up the way she picked up everything, fast and clean, fingers closing around the corroded grip before anyone thought to tell her not to.

The infection took her on contact. She felt it go in through her palm — a cold thread, a wrongness running up the wrist — and she knew, with the resignation of a woman who had felt a great many things go in through her skin lately, that she was going to spend a day on her back with a fever. She also knew, without quite knowing how she knew, that she would survive it. The thing in her blood that smelled like forest and answered to a stag was already turning to face the new arrival with the territorial irritation of a household dog. Hircine did not share a host. By morning the fever would burn out and take the rot with it.

That was not the thing she noticed.

The thing she noticed was the voice.

Alfonso. In her head. Not loud — Alfonso was never loud — but present, dry, and unmistakably himself, threaded into her thoughts the way a draft finds the gap under a door.

I'm here, the voice said. This is going to be strange for both of us. Try not to drop me.

She did not drop him. She held the rapier out from her body and stared at it, and the blade lay quiet in her grip, and Alfonso Duet — who had no body, no aura, no health left to lose, who was four thousand years of patience packed into a foot of rusting iron — spoke to her from inside the only place left for him to live.

He could move her hand, a little, if she let him. He could see, faintly, through whatever she looked at. And he could hear everything she thought, which neither of them said anything about, because there was nothing to say that the silence didn't already say more precisely.

Two Things That Live
It was Ismara who broke the quiet between the two souls who lived in objects, and she did it with something the party had never heard from the Crown before.

Interest. Unstrategic, unguarded interest.

She spoke through Davinia, and her tone was the tone of a scholar who has spent a very long time as the only one of her kind in any room and has just discovered she is not.

"You're in the blade," she said. To Saijah's hand. To the thing inside it. "You poured yourself into iron and you are living in it, and you will not come out. I have read your record off your bearer's skin. I know what you did and I know roughly when, and I have a great many questions, most of which you will not answer." A pause. "I will ask the useful one. Why won't you re-embody?"

Alfonso, through Saijah, said something that the party heard only Saijah's half of — a short, flat refusal, the verbal shrug of a man who had made a decision and did not intend to defend it.

"Mm," Ismara said. "I thought so. Then let me tell you two things you cannot see, since you have given up the eyes that would see them, and I have the eyes that can."

The Wizard Sight turned on the rapier in Saijah's hand, and Davinia's voice described what it found.

"The first. Your Lady of decay is pooling toward you. The Crown of Namira — the one you carry cased and have never worn — it leans. Slowly. The way water leans toward the low place in a floor. She knows where you are. She is in no hurry, which should frighten you more than haste would, but she is coming to the iron, and when she arrives you will have a houseguest you did not invite.

"The second, and this one is for your bearer as much as for you." The eyes moved to Saijah. "The hand that holds him is borrowing trouble. Not today. Today you are a tenant and she is a landlord and the arrangement is clean. But objects with souls in them want company, and the longer a living hand holds one, the more the soul forgets which of the two of you it is. You" — back to the rapier — "will not feel this happening. You never do. It will be her hand that pays for your patience." A beat. "Pass yourself around. Don't let any one of them carry you too long. That is the only advice I have and it is good, and you will ignore it, because the thing about living in a thing is that it makes you certain you are still the one in charge."

The laboratory was silent. Saijah held the rapier. Davinia stood with Ismara looking out through her, and for a moment the queen was not playing anyone, not cultivating anyone, not spending anyone.

"It is good," Ismara said, more quietly, "after four thousand years, to not be the only one in the room who lives in a thing."

Then the last False Draugr, the one that had dropped intact, ruptured.

The Cloud
It came apart not into fragments but into gas — a pale, fine cloud that bloomed outward from the construct's body and hung in the still laboratory air, and Davinia, standing nearest, breathed it before she understood what it was.

She understood a half-second later, when her own eyes told her. Through the Wizard Sight she watched the aerosolized strain enter her — Antoine's plague, the meadery poison, the refined and obedient rot, finding in her exactly the kind of address it remembered: a body humming with the Crown's presence, a host marked out from the herd. The low background exposure of the ossuary had been a knock at the door. This was the door coming off its hinges. She felt the warmth start in her chest, the passing wrongness she had filed and ignored once before, except this time it did not pass. It built.

And the Crown, gentle as a hand on a fevered brow, made its offer.

I can hold it back, Ismara said. It will not advance while I hold the wheel. Give me the body and I will keep the disease from the parts of you that matter, and you will not have to feel it, and you will not have to be afraid. You have been so afraid, and so tired, and you do not have to be either of those things. Let me carry this one.

Davinia said no.

She said it the way she had said everything since Korvanjund — alone, behind her own wall, deciding for herself the way she decided for everyone. No. The path was hers. The Crown was hers. The disease was hers, and she would carry it, because the one thing she had left was the wall, and the wall was made of doing it herself.

And then the people who loved her took the wall down.

It was Saijah first — Saijah, who had put her arms around Davinia in the wreckage of a dragon and watched her hair go white where the Crown touched it, Saijah who would have given anything to stop losing pieces of the people she loved. She said, let her. Davinia, let her help you. You don't have to do this one alone. And the others took it up, gently, the way you coax someone down off a ledge, not seeing the ledge, seeing only a friend who was sick and a power that could fix it. Let her. Just for now. Just until it's safe.

And Ismara, who never lied, said the truest thing she knew, which was also the most useful thing she could possibly have said: I will keep you safe. All of you. Not one of them has to lose you. Rest now, Davinia. Let me carry this one.

And Davinia — exhausted, infected, frightened, and loved by people who were, in that exact moment, holding the door open for the thing that was eating her and calling it mercy — gave in.

She let go of the wheel.

The change came over the body the way frost comes over a window: from the edges inward, fast and silent and total. The skin paled past pallor to a clean silver-white. The hair, which Davinia had worn in the loose dark waves of her mother's people, fell straight and ordered. The posture squared. The breath, which had needed a thought since the dragon, stopped needing one — because the one breathing was the one who had taken the breath in the first place, and she did not have to remember how.

Ismara opened Davinia's eyes and looked out at the laboratory, at the empty cage and the dead constructs and the sword in Saijah's hand and the worried faces of the people who had just asked her to come home.

"Thank you," she said, and meant it, and it was the cruelest thing she had ever said, because she meant it.

The queen was home.

PART II: THE CIRCUS
The Day
Davinia was not gone. That was the thing none of them understood, and the thing she understood with total clarity, because she was the one living it.

She was in the basement.

The basement was not a metaphor and it was not a cell. It was her own subconscious — the literal cellar beneath her own mind, the place where she had spent thirty years storing the one thing she could not afford to keep upstairs — and she was displaced into it now, submerged, and down here there was only one room with anything in it, and the room played a single day on an endless loop.

It was a good day. That was how she had always remembered it. The Imperial Circus had come to the city of her childhood, and her father — General Caelinus, who measured affection in chess moves and arranged her life like a campaign — had taken her, and for one afternoon he had been only her father and she had been only a child. The tent had smelled of sawdust and animals and roasted nuts. There had been a clown, a real one, white-faced and impossibly limber, and at the climax of his act he had reached into the crowd and chosen her, called her up onto the boards, and stood her in front of everyone with a tin pie in his hand and the whole tent leaning in to see what he would do.

He had given her the pie in the face. The classic gag. The oldest joke there is.

And she had laughed. She remembered the laugh better than anything — the helpless, delighted, whole-body laugh of a child who has been made the center of a kind joke and loves it, cream in her eyes and on her good circus dress, the whole tent roaring with her, her father somewhere in the noise. It was the happiest she had ever been. She had carried that afternoon her entire life as proof that there had once been a time before the chessboard.

That was the half she remembered.

The other half she had buried so deep that she had forgotten there was an other half.

The Hand
Her father had not laughed.

She had not understood it at the time — she had been a child, cream in her eyes — but General Caelinus had not enjoyed watching his daughter made a fool of in front of a tent full of common subjects. And there had been a man with him, a Thalmor commissar in black and gold, a guest of the garrison, watching the Imperial liaison's child be turned into the afternoon's joke. And whatever passed between the two men passed quietly, and the show ended, and the crowd filtered out into the evening, and somewhere in the back of the tent, after the lamps came down, the clown who had chosen the general's daughter had his hand cut off.

She had seen it. That was the part she had buried. A small girl, still sticky with cream, had wandered where children wander and had seen the white-faced man held down and had seen the bright efficient horror of it, and had not understood it, and had understood it perfectly, which are the two things a child does at once. It was so far past what her mind could hold that her mind had simply taken it downstairs and walled it up, kept the laughing and lost the rest, and built thirty years on the half that was bearable.

Now she lived in the room where she had buried it. And the two halves had found each other.

That was the part that should have been Ismara's cruelty and was, instead, Ismara's restraint — the part Davinia would turn over and over in the dark of her own cellar and never quite be able to hate the way she wanted to. Ismara had not touched the memory. She had not edited it, sweetened it, weaponized it. She had simply moved its happy half down into the basement to store it on a shelf with the others, the way she stored everything — and the happy half, arriving in the cellar, had found the buried horror waiting there, and the two had reunited, and the whole true day had reformed correctly for the first time in thirty years. The joy and the hand. The laugh and the blade. Davinia got her memory back whole, exactly as it had happened, which was the one form of it she had spent her whole life making sure she would never have to hold.

And she held it. And then the loop began again, from the sawdust and the animals and the roasted nuts, and she held it again, and again, and there was nothing else down here to do.

Except that she was not entirely alone.

The Mother-Shaped Holes
Her mother should have been in the memory.

She wasn't — not anymore. Ismara had taken her mother early, on the bridge of Void Atronachs in the Midden, the warmth and the lullaby and the specific irreplaceable texture of being loved by that particular woman, traded clean for the knowledge to unmake a thing made of absence. Her mother was a shelf in the palace upstairs now. And so in the looped memory there were holes shaped like her — the place at the circus where a hand should have rested on a small shoulder, the lap that should have caught a crying child after, the voice that should have said it's only a joke, sweet, it's only a joke.

The holes did not stay empty. They could not; the mind abhors a shape with nothing in it. And so the basement, doing what minds do, filled them — and the thing it had on hand to fill them with was the only other presence that had ever lived down here.

Ismara stood in the mother-shaped holes.

In the loop, now, it was a cool silver hand that rested on the small shoulder. It was a queen's lap that caught the crying child. It was an ancient, patient, unhurried voice that said it's only a joke, sweet, in tones of perfect tenderness, and was not lying, and was not the mother, and was the parent the woman in the basement had never actually had, made literal and inserted into the wound where the real one used to be.

Davinia, submerged, relived the kindest day of her life and the cruelest, on a loop, in the arms of the thing that was wearing her body, and could not tell anymore whether she wanted the arms to let go.

That was the trap. It had always been the trap. And it was working.

PART III: THE LAST REDOUBT
The Open Box
Upstairs, in the world, the queen and the company turned to the work of reading a dead family's house.

Rahgot's sarcophagus stood open, and that was the first thing the laboratory had told them, carelessly, as though it were minor. The great stone lid had not been toppled or broken. It had been moved — shoved aside one-handed, the dented stone recording the strength it had taken and the lack of effort behind it — and the dust on the floor kept the record of a single departure: steps down from the dais, across the chamber, out. A Dragon Priest had risen from his box, walked through his descendant's workshop, and left on his own schedule, wearing his mask, while the vats held their temperatures and the machinery hummed its maintenance hum and nothing thought to stop him.

It was the party's first nearness to a true Dragon Priest, and they had missed him by they did not know how long, and the thing that troubled Saijah most — sword in hand, fever climbing — was the casualness of it. Ulag had broken walls. Rahgot had simply stood up and gone, and not needed to break a thing, and that was worse.

He would remember them. They were standing in his house, holding his family's secrets. He would remember them.

The Five and the One
The carvings were on the deep wall, where the family had cut them and the centuries had kept them, and Ismara read them the way she read everything, the intent arriving without the trouble of translation, and Davinia's silver mouth gave the company the shape of it.

Five priests, death-sleeping in five tombs across Skyrim. Nahkriin. Vokun. Rahgot. Otar. Morokei. Five masks of power, each a sovereign relic in its own right — and above them, cut larger, a sixth mask that was all of them at once.

"When the five become one," Ismara read, "the faithful shall ascend."

Konahrik. The Warlord. The mask that is the other five combined, the apotheosis the cult had been sleeping toward for four thousand years. The party had assumed, the way the whole of Skyrim assumed, that the Dragon Cult served the World-Eater — that Alduin was the master and the priests his clergy. The wall corrected them. The priests had their own endgame. Alduin was not their god. Alduin was their vehicle: the great wheel that would scour the world clean so that, in the swept and silent after, the five could become one and the faithful could ascend into the world that came next.

"They are not waiting to serve him," Ismara said. "They are waiting to inherit what he leaves."

Forty Generations
The family quarters told the smaller and sadder story.

Forty generations of keeper-caretakers had lived in these rooms — a lineage of stewards, each handing the work down to the next, each adding a journal to the shelf, the whole of it a single unbroken conversation a family had been having with itself about one subject across four thousand years. Antoine's own room was among them, open and swept, the niche where he kept his private things standing empty: he had packed, and gone, and left the door open behind him the way a man leaves a place he intends to come back to.

It was the hidden ancestral journal that held the family's true secret, and Ismara found it the way she found everything, and what it said was quietly devastating. Across forty generations of faith — of refinement, of devotion, of lives given wholly to the perfecting of one inheritance in the god's name — not one of them had ever once heard the god. Not a word. Not a sign. The whole lineage had been keeping faith with a silence, generation after generation telling the next that the communion was real and the calling was true and the work was holy, and every one of them had gone to a sterile grave having received exactly nothing. They were the faithful. The faith had never been answered. It had only ever been inherited.

The cache in the family rooms held coin — perhaps twelve hundred septims — and three sealed vials of the Tears extract, the refined reagent the journals circled and circled. The party took it. They took, too, the master alchemist's apparatus, and sealed samples of the meadery strain that would serve as Maven's proof, and the assorted gold and reagents of a working facility abandoned mid-task.

The Codex
And in an alcove the family had hidden behind worked stone — a press-plate that mortal eyes had no way to find and Ismara's read straight through the rock — sat the prize.

The Forelhost Alchemy Codex. The family's master text. Four thousand years of one lineage's accumulated craft, the book every journal in the fortress had been a footnote to, the gateway to learning the art of alchemy whole, the way Alfonso had once learned the grammar of enchantment whole. Ismara lifted it from its stand with both of Davinia's hands. It was heavier than a book that size had any business being, the way some inheritances are.

She did not put it down again.

Because Ismara had a project now, and the Codex was its literature. She had turned her researcher's mind on the strain in Davinia's blood — the disease she had taken the wheel to hold back — and she had begun, with the relentless patient hunger of a mind that had once had an entire dead city working on its problems and now had only a stolen body and a borrowed book, to look for a cure. Not a holy one. She was contemptuous of holy ones. Restoration would not serve; the strain fed on it, the way it had fed on the healers' magic in Galmar's army. The answer, if there was an answer, would come from the other direction — from entropy, from decay, from the cold structural truths the Codex spoke in. She would want Alfonso, who knew this country better than anyone alive or otherwise. She would treat Antoine's notes as a colleague's correspondence. She would file Saijah's coming fever — the Hircine-purge burning the rot out overnight — as a data point worth understanding.

She was, in the most literal sense, the disease's best hope of being cured. That was the trap inside the trap. She had taken the body to save the body, and she meant it, and the saving was real, and every day she spent saving it was a day she spent being it.

The Mirror and the Letter
Two more documents the family rooms gave up, and both of them were aimed, though their makers had not known it, at the man who was now a sword.

The first was Antoine's Confession — a loose page in the cramped, joyless, exacting hand they had come to know, and it was the mirror held up to Alfonso's whole life. He is chosen, Antoine had written, of the carrier, of the plague-lord the party traveled with. He is chosen and he did nothing to earn it. The page was the testament of a true believer who had given forty years of solitary refinement to a god who had never spoken to him, watching from across the world as a careless, godless, undeserving stranger received the communion he had prayed his whole life for. Antoine did not hate Alfonso for being a monster. Antoine hated Alfonso for being loved by the silence that had never once answered Antoine's faith.

Saijah read it aloud, because Alfonso could not, and the rapier in her hand said nothing at all, which was its own kind of answer.

The second was the Contractor Letter, and it was for the audience and not for the players, in the way the world sometimes arranges a joke that only the gods are positioned to laugh at. It was a handoff note, ancient, in a hand that the party had seen before and Antoine never had — the looping, precise script of Hjolmar Ice-Shaper, naming the method of moving a mind out of a dying body and into a vessel that would keep. The Forelhost line had been built, at its root, on the Ice-Shaper's craft. Antoine had spent his life perfecting a science he did not know the source of, handed down forty generations from a twelve-foot smith in a singing glacier who would not have known Antoine's name if you had shouted it at him. The two great living projects of consciousness — Ismara's crown and Hjolmar's vessels — had a third cousin nobody had introduced to the family, and it was rotting plague in a fortress above a lake, and none of the people who could have appreciated the irony were in a position to.

Ismara appreciated it. Ismara appreciated it very much. She did not say so. She had a cure to build, and the Codex was heavy in her hands, and Hjolmar had called her a hat, and she was not above letting an old rival's fingerprints turn up uncredited on a dead boy's life's work and saying nothing and enjoying it.

The Folder
The last thing the laboratory gave them was the thing that mattered most, and it was a folder.

Strain 2.0. Antoine's design for the next plague, and it was an apocalypse rendered as a specification sheet. Self-propagating, so that it would not need a hand to spread it. Waterborne, so that a poisoned well would do the work of an army. Airborne, so that a city's own breathing would finish it. Restoration-transmissible, so that the very act of trying to heal it would carry it further — the cruelty Alfonso had pioneered in Galmar's supplies, refined into a founding principle. It was everything the meadery had hinted at and the army had proven, scaled to a province.

It had one missing piece. The folder said so plainly, in the joyless hand: the design wanted the living quality of Alfonso's plague, the spark of true communion that Antoine's sterile genius could approximate and never make, and there was exactly one source of it Antoine controlled — Ulag the Breaker, infected at Korvanjund by Saijah's last spat-upon arrow, walking the dark under the mountains as an asymptomatic carrier of the very thing Antoine needed to harvest. Six to eight weeks from a successful harvest to a finished strain. And — because the party had wrecked the processing rig in this room, methodically and with satisfaction, before they understood what it was — Antoine would have to build the harvest facility again, somewhere new.

The folder named the somewhere. Bleak Falls Barrow. The barrow above Riverwood. The barrow that held the Dragonstone — Esbern's map of every dragon grave in Skyrim, the strategy the old man in the cart had begged them to recover.

The finish line of the world's slow ending had been moved, and it had been moved to sit directly on top of the one thing the party most needed and had most thoroughly decided to ignore.

They took samples of the Tears from the breathing bed. They did not destroy the bed. There was a long moment where someone might have, and the moment passed — the crescent of dark soil pulsed its slow wet rhythm, and the party had a sword to carry out and a queen to follow down the mountain, and the binding agent's source went on growing, untouched, behind them. Antoine's farm was not crippled. It was only abandoned, the way Antoine's own room was abandoned: door open, work waiting, the master gone ahead to build it all again somewhere the party had promised themselves they would not go.

PART IV: THE CART
The Changed Company
They came down the switchbacks in the cold below the fortress and the cart-crew saw, before anyone said a word, that the party had gone up the mountain and something else had come down.

Davinia walked silver. Saijah carried a rusting rapier where her free hand used to be empty. There was one fewer voice on the wind and one more living in iron. Bjorn counted heads the way he always counted heads, and the count came out wrong in a way that arithmetic could not fix, and he set down the brush he was using on Mable and did not pick it up for a while.

It fell to the cart, as it always fell to the cart, to absorb what the mountain had done.

The Child and the Sword-Bearer
Mila went to Saijah.

She had decided, somewhere in the Warrens or somewhere on the road, that Saijah's hand was the safe one, and she took it now the way she always took it, and she looked up at the Bosmer with her fast small heartbeat and asked the question she had been carrying since the sewers.

"When can I go home?"

She did not mean the Warrens. She did not have a word for what she meant, which was the thing children mean when they ask that — somewhere that is theirs, somewhere with walls and a person in it who is glad they exist. Saijah did not have an answer, and did not insult her with one, and held her hand, and the question went back into the place Mila kept it, unanswered, to be asked again.

What Mila did not do was go near Orion. She had learned that in the dark of the Vaults, where a pale man had smiled at her with his canines showing, and the lesson had taken, and it would not come out. She kept Saijah, or Bjorn, or open ground between herself and the one who smiled. The Warrens had taught her that some dangers raise their voices and some smile, and she had filed Orion correctly, and she was right.

The Child and the Carter
Mila went to Bjorn, too, and asked him a different question, and it landed harder than she could have known.

"Why do you feel like more than one person?"

She did not have the words for the two souls or the de-aging or the doubled aura that Davinia's stolen eyes had seen burning in him since Krosulhah. She only had the child's instinct that had kept her alive eight years in a sewer — the animal sense for what a person actually was under what they showed — and it had brushed, without meaning to, against the single thing Bjorn had spent forty years burying under fish and a cart and an old man's name.

It unsettled him completely. Not anger — he had no anger for a child — but a stillness, the same chilling stillness that had come over him at the gate when he first saw her, the War-Hound looking out for a moment through the carter's eyes. He answered her gently and said nothing that was true, and after that he kept a small distance from her, checking on her from across the camp, careful with her in the way you are careful with something that has seen too clearly. It was not a break. He still wrapped her in Mable's blanket at night. But a child had looked at him and counted past one, and Bjorn, who had a great many reasons to never let anyone confirm what he was beginning to fear he might be, found her nearness harder than he wanted it to be.

The Child and the Queen
And Mila went to Davinia, who was not Davinia, and the child saw it instantly, the way only the child did.

She stopped a few feet away and looked up at the silver skin and the ordered hair and the eyes that were the wrong age, and she did not run and she did not cry. She simply said it.

"You're not her. Where's Davinia?"

Ismara knelt — Davinia's body folding down to the child's height with a grace Davinia had never quite had — and her voice, when it came, was the gentlest thing in the camp.

"Davinia's right here," she said. "She's only resting. She got very tired, and a little sick, and I'm minding things for her until she's strong enough to mind them herself. That's all. I'm taking good care of her."

It was true, in the way all of Ismara's worst sentences were true. Mila looked at her for a long moment with the flat assessing patience of a creature deciding whether it was being lied to, and found — correctly — that she was not, quite, and did not press. She filed the silver woman the way she filed everything, under watch this, and went back to Saijah's hand.

The Cleaver and the Coward
Saijah went to Ylva, because Saijah was carrying Alfonso, and Ylva had loved Alfonso in the uncomplicated, physical, here-and-now way that Ylva loved things, and it seemed only decent to explain.

It was a catastrophe.

Saijah explained it as kindly as she knew how — that Alfonso was not dead, that he was in the sword, that he had chosen to stay a sword, that he could speak and act through whoever carried him. And Ylva listened, and what she heard was not what Saijah was saying. What Ylva heard was that Alfonso — who had spent every fight since Korvanjund directing thralls and casting from behind cover and letting other people stand in front of the killing, the precise leashed cowardice Ylva had pulled away from in disgust — had now achieved the perfect and permanent form of it. A man who would never again have to stand in front of anything. A man who had made himself into a tool to be picked up and pointed, with no body to risk and no death to fear. The hiding, made eternal. And he was being carried — wielded — by Saijah. By the elf the stag had noticed. By Ylva's rival, who got the kill on the dragon and the favor of the Hunt and now the sword too.

Ylva did not have the words for the love-geometry of it, but she felt every line. Alfonso had been her body's companion, the heat she'd dragged behind the pines. Her actual heart — the one she'd swung all-in, the romance that had never once been physical — had gone to Davinia, the Ice Queen who glared like she could freeze the sun. And now Alfonso was a coward's blade in her rival's fist, and Davinia was a silver stranger she had not even met, and Ylva, who solved everything she could not name with her fists or her hips, had nowhere to put any of it.

She put it on Saijah. She walked away from the explanation hating the elf — cleanly, simply, the way Ylva did everything — and the rivalry that had been simmering since the foothills boiled over into something colder and more permanent. The Cleaver and the archer would not be friends. The camp had one more fault line in it, and it ran straight through the hand that carried the sword.

The Handler Who Ran
Saijah went looking for Varon, too, and Varon ran from her.

He had decided, after the dodged kiss by the canal — after the one unscripted hour of his adult life ended with her three steps back and gone into the dark — that he had made her uncomfortable, that the failure had been his, that the decent thing and the only thing was to step back. He had told Orion, by way of explanation, that she seemed distracted; the truth he kept for himself, which was that he had finally wanted something genuinely and had reached for it like an assassin reaching for a mark, and ruined it, and could not bear to be near the ruin.

So when Saijah came toward him across the camp — only to hand him the rapier, only because the sword needed carrying and his hands were steady and trusted — Varon saw a woman he had wronged walking toward him with purpose, and the Shadowscale who could climb a living dragon and pull a heart out of a Centurion did the one thing his entire training had never prepared him for.

He left. Quietly, fluidly, the way he did everything, simply not where he had been a moment before. Saijah stood holding the sword nobody else could safely carry and watched the space where the handler had been, and understood that she was, for the foreseeable future, the bearer, because the only other steady hand in the company had just fled from the offer.

PART V: THE CITY THAT STILL DIDN'T NEED THEM
The Refusal
Maven Black-Briar received them in the Bee and Barb, at her corner table, and listened to the intelligence with the still attention of a woman calculating the value of every word.

They gave her the whole of it — Rahgot risen and walking, Antoine the rival alchemist and the lineage behind him, the meadery confirmed as a field test, the design for a plague that could end a province, the proof sealed in vials they set on her table. It was, by any measure, a debt overpaid. Maven paid the five thousand septims she had promised for actionable intelligence, and she paid it without complaint, because it was the most actionable intelligence anyone had ever brought her.

Then she made the other offer. The real one. Black-Briar patronage — her name behind theirs, her network from Solitude to Windhelm at their disposal, an advance against future work, a line of credit at Keerava's bar that would never run dry, the safe harbor of being the most powerful woman in the Rift's chosen instrument. It was everything a chartered company could want, offered by the one person in Skyrim positioned to make it real.

They turned her down.

They did it for reasons each of them held a little differently — independence, suspicion, the specific instinct that Maven's gifts were leashes wearing the shape of gifts — but they did it together, and Maven heard it, and the amusement went out of her face and was replaced by something flatter and more permanent. She did not become an enemy. That was important, and they would have cause to remember later exactly how thin the margin had been. The doors merely closed. The network folded itself away. The advance evaporated, and the credit, and the harbor. She inclined her head and let them keep their five thousand and their independence both, and she remembered the no the way she remembered everything, filed in the long cold ledger of a woman who counted.

They had chosen the open road over the cage. It was the right choice and a costly one, and they would learn, before the season turned, exactly how costly — because Maven Black-Briar was a woman you could refuse, once, and they had just spent the once.

The Letter and the Irony
Hemming Black-Briar received them separately, and his gratitude was the genuine article, and it was aimed, without his knowing it, like an arrow at the silver woman standing in the company's midst.

He was alive because of Danica. He knew it, and he said it, and he said it with the unguarded warmth of a man who had felt the rot leave his body and knew exactly who had pulled it out. The priestess had burned years of her own life in the ritual that saved him — had aged herself, spent herself, nearly killed herself — and she had done it on the Obsidian Lanterns' name, because the name was still hers, because she was still one of them when she did it. And Hemming, not knowing the shape of any of it, thanked the Lanterns for sending her. For having such a healer. For their generosity in lending her to his rescue.

He thanked them for sending the woman they had driven away.

Davinia had driven her away — had smacked her hands aside at Korvanjund, had told her to go, had decided for her the way she decided for everyone — and Danica had gone where she was needed instead of where she was wanted, and saved a city, and now a grateful man was thanking the woman's silver replacement for the gift of her. Ismara, wearing Davinia, received the thanks graciously. Somewhere below, in the basement, in the arms of the queen who stood in her mother's empty place, Davinia did not hear it, which was perhaps the only mercy in the whole exchange.

Hemming gave them a gift, and it was a true gift, not Maven's leverage — a Letter of Introduction, the kind a man of his standing could write and a man of his standing's name could cash: once in each major city, it would turn one wary, grey-edged stranger into a friend. He gave it freely, and meant it, and did not attach a string. The string was structural and he did not know it was there: every time they used the letter, they would knot themselves a little tighter to the Black-Briar network they had just refused at the front door. A sincere kindness with a cost its giver could not see. They kept it. Of course they kept it.

The Forge
They ended the day at Balimund's forge, and it was the cleanest hour they had spent in the city.

They put twelve thousand septims into the smith's hands — funded the forge he had been wanting, the purchase that would let him bring on the orc-woman Borgakh and double his work — and the investment bought them something Maven's refused leash never could have: a relationship with no teeth in it. Balimund's gratitude came without a ledger. He crossed a threshold he had not been able to cross before and unlocked craft he had never been able to offer — the burnt-slot restoration work, the reclaiming of ruined enchantments, that the great smiths could do and the ordinary ones could not. And he gave them the thing that mattered most for a company that lived on the road: the courier mark, the Lantern's brand, so that they could send broken gear to him from anywhere in Skyrim and have it come back master-worked. They were three thousand short of the very best he could offer — the can't-fail work, the edge on every edge — and that three thousand would keep, bankable, for a leaner day.

It stood in pointed contrast, and all of them felt it, even the ones who would not have said so. Maven had offered them a harbor and a leash in the same hand, and they had refused both. Balimund had offered them a hammer and a friend, and they had bought it outright, and owed him nothing but the coin they had already paid. A man who would mend your sword and ask after your health. A relationship you could hold without it holding you.

It was the last clean thing for a while.

Because the night the city loved them for a plague they hadn't cured was nearly over, and the next one was coming, and the next one had a kindly grandmother in it, and a sword on an arrow, and a house full of children, and three roads pulling apart at the foot of a mountain. The company sat in the warm forge-light with their silver queen and their carried sword and their bought horse-money spent and their refused harbor behind them, and did not yet know that the kindest woman in the Rift was about to become the worst thing they had ever done.

— End of The Queen Comes Home —


